{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01G1uM64G5ZrKZfJSBeTSeaj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see that the Ray head IS running a Ray Client server on port 10001 (`/home/ray/anaconda3/bin/python -m ray.util.client.server --address=10.244.0.229:6379 --host=0.0.0.0 --port=10001 --mode=proxy --runtime-env-agent-address=http://10.244.0.229:54701`). \n\nBut the Kubernetes Service only exposes port 6379. Port 10001 is not exposed via the Service.\n\nOK so let me re-examine this. The task says:\n- \"Update the job script so it connects to ray-head:6379.\"\n- The service exposes port 6379 which is the GCS port.\n\nThe correct Ray 2.x way to connect to a cluster as a driver using the GCS address is `ray.init(address=\"ray-head:6379\")`. But the issue we're seeing is that it's looking for a local `node_ip_address.json` file. The client pod has the same session directory as the head pod (`session_2026-07-01_18-24-22_713154_13`), but it's missing the `node_ip_address.json` file, which is odd.\n\nActually, I'm realizing both pods are running on the same Kubernetes node (`karma-2-control-plane`), so they shouldn't be sharing the same `/tmp` filesystem since pods have isolated filesystem namespaces. But the session directory names are identical, which shouldn't happen unless they're somehow sharing storage or the client pod has leftover state from a previous Ray process. The error occurs because when the client pod calls `ray.init(address=\"ray-head:6379\")`, it retrieves the remote cluster's session name and creates a local session directory with that same name—so the directory path contains the head node's startup timestamp even though the client pod started later. The client then can't find the `node_ip_address.json` file in that local session directory because it doesn't have the necessary cluster metadata. The issue is that when `ray.init(address=\"ray-head:6379\")` is called on the client pod